item.title: Basic Definition and Description
item.dc:creator: jhesed
item.content:encoded:
[one_fifth] [/one_fifth] [four_fifth_last padding="0 0 0 10px"]

Overview

The C8 Campaign is a set off extensive programs and projects that will eventually define the specific calling and identity of the JESUS: Sovereign Overcoming Shepherd Christian Church.

In a nut shell, this campaign may be called a total church program involving eight major areas of ministries and purposes of Christians and a local Christian Church; and culminating in an adequate preparation of the body of the Lord Jesus Christ for the end-times, until the return of our dear Master and Savior.

The 8 Major Components

  1. Worship
  2. Evangelism
  3. Discipleship
  4. Fellowship
  5. Intercession
  6. Healing
  7. Temporal Excellence
  8. Community Outreach

The Cs and the 8s in the C8 Campaign

The “C” in C8 Campaign refers to the eight words that describe the believer of the Lord Jesus Christ in relation to each other and the local church, as well as their collective tasks

The “8” in C8 Campaign, meanwhile, refers to the lessons and challenges the number eight (8) in the Bible present to the Christians, and the local church.

The Three Phases of the Campaign

This Campaign has three major phases; each of which has eight fundamental components. The three phases covers this year, 2014, and proceeds until the return of the Lord Jesus Christ.

The First Phase is perceived to be the longest. It focuses on the eight major components of what is supposed to be the main tasks and privileges of a truly maturing and well-rounded Christian church.

The Second Phase is actually an extension of the eight thrust/component of the First Phase, which is Community Outreach. This is about a comprehensive system of reaching out to communities, beginning with Angono where the JSOS Main is located.  It will then proceed to reach out communities where the official JSOS Christian Church members reside.  Finally, this Second Phase will focus on establishing daughter churches and/or ministry satellites as the Lord leads.

The Third Phase of the C8 Campaign will occur much later. It will focus on eight major thrusts that will network with other churches and denominations in evangelizing peoples and communities, in assisting in the mobilization of Christian organizations to spread the gospel further, and in the preparation of the body of Christ for the coming escathological events.

The Simple Beginning

The vision and mission for the C8 Campaign were initially presented through a series of sermons last September, 2013. 

If and when considerably implemented together by the local church, the C8 Campaign, will certainly be a mighty tool of our great God in effecting a well-rounded, and growing church, both in quality and quantity, in its local setting.

[/four_fifth_last]

item.title: Meaning of "C" in C8 Campaign
item.dc:creator: jhesed
item.content:encoded:
[one_fifth]

[/one_fifth]

[four_fifth_last padding="0 0 0 20px"]

It can be said that the C8 Campaign is a total church program that involves all aspects of the Christian life.
It aims to facilitate the maturity and productivity of all the members of the JSOS Christian Church ( Kapamuso ) and the other partner churches and Christian individuals. It also aims to prepare them to the return of the Lord Jesus Christ and the accompanying events.

To better understand the comprehensiveness of the said campaign, let's look at the eight meanings of "C" in it.

CHRISTIANITY on 8

It refers to the things that a Christian needs to know about the information, principles and challenges the Number EIGHT (8) presents as far as the Bible is concerned.

We at the JSOS Christian Church believe that every part of the Bible is sovereignly planned by God. No word, number or instances were used there without purpose. That goes with the use of the number 8.
Some Bible numerology experts say prominent numbers have special meanings. For instance, 7 is often called the number of divine perfection. The number 2 denotes emphasis and sweetness; the number 10 points to human government and perfection while the number 12 refers to God's people.

The number 8's messages, while not as easily revealed as those numbers, have certainly meaningful implications as well.

For instance, did you know that God commanded the Jewish men to be circumcised on their eighth day? Even the Lord Jesus Christ Himself was circumcised eight days after he was born. Did you also know that the animals God meant to be sacrificed became worthy for offering only after eight days? There were also only eight survivors to the Great Deluge. These and many more uses of the number seem to convey vital implications and challenges.
While we don't believe in superstition and plain luck, we are convinced that a thorough study of the instances the number 8 was used in the Bible will show us many meaningful things that will add up challenges and inspiration in our Christian lives.

CONFORMITY towards 8

This refers to our members' personal recognition of the information and the challenges the messages God relays through the Biblical use of the number 8.

This means it is always best for Christians to acknowledge that studying on this matter is helpful in their own Christian lives.

For instance, realizing that the Jewish males were commanded to have their circumcision at eight days old, and that their animals were declared by God to be worthy for offering once these reached eight days old, should make Christians recognize the necessity to offer themselves to God early on in life.

COMMITMENT for 8

This refers to the commitment to the principles and challenges the messages of the number 8 present in the Bible.

Not only do the Christians acknowledge the practical implications of this realization, but more importantly, commit their time and efforts in striving to fulfil the challenges it presents. Over-all, the JSOS Christian Church members are expected to support totally C8 Campaign.

CURRICULUM of 8

This refers to a comprehensive curriculum that comprises all essential elements of a truly maturing and reproducing Christian life. Each unit features eight topics which ideally runs for eight sessions, or two months.

It will serve as the main discipleship program of the church, and includes, among others:

    • Eight Assurances in the Christian Life

    • Eight Steps to Genuine Christian Maturity

    • Eight Qualities of a Chris-like Character

    • Eight Major Christian Doctrines

    • Eight Key Steps to Serving God

COMMUNITY of 8

This particular thrust refers to the holding of programs and activities which will develop dynamic and intensifying fellowship among the JSOS official members through small group( kapamuso ). It includes the implementation of the eight-part Covenant of a Caring Group and the 16 "One Anothers" of the NIV New Testament ( love, greet, accept, forgive, etc. )

In this project, church members will be divided into small groups called Care Flocks. They will stay together for at least two months, discussing either the SHA ( Sermon Huddle for Application ) and/or the official C8 Curriculum.

After about three months, they will be assigned to other Care Flocks to maximize closeness with the rest of the JSOS Family

CIRCLE of 8

This is called a circle because the main thrust is to let each member of the Care Flock develop in every possible way of ministering to God and others. During this period, each member take turns in being in-charge of the CF program , prayer, testimony and special number.

Through this, various Christian and leadership skills are also taught and practiced one by one. This includes the holding of personal devotion, intercession, Scripture memory, fasting, personal soulwinning, and particular leadership skills.

In effect, the resulting product of the Circle of 8 is a Christian who is willing and ready to minister in various ways.

CHRIST-LIKENESS in 8

This is the highest goal of the C8 Campaign for every member of the JSOS Christian Church: to be conformed to the 'image' of the Lord Jesus Christ.

In this thrust, comprehensive Bible study and meditation on the eight major qualities of a matured Christian from St. Peter's list is undertaken. This list is mirrored to every member in such a way that he will be personally motivated to develop a Christ-like character. He will be using the official personal planning worksheet of the JSOS to monitor his development on each quality.

Of course, group admonition, reminder, monitoring and practical supports will be given to each member by his Care Flock for this cause.

CHURCH of 8

This may be considered the most prophetic thrust of the C8 Campaign.

We want every Kapamuso to become mature and productive Christian and member of the JSOS Christian Church. Such individual maturity will eventually make a gathering of even a small group of members become a virtually small but stable church.

This small group of small believers will then be entrusted, in due time, to have their own communion, praying for the sick , water baptism and other church tasks.

To do this, there will be times when members of the JSOS Christian Church will be grouped according to their residential locations.

This practice will make the JSOS Christian Church relatively strong from the so-called grass roots.

This will be an huge advantage in case of unforeseen circumstances like calamities or severe persecution, when the actual gathering of the entire church membership is difficult or dangerous.

[/four_fifth_last]

Mission

The JSOS Youth Ministry is driven by the heart and movement that support the C8 Campaign of the JSOS Church by reaching out to its youths, empowering them for their holistic Christian growth and secular well-roundedness.

Vision

The JSOS Youth Ministry has a mature and solid organization with an established culture of worship, intercession, camaraderie, evangelism and discipleship, and leadership and servanthood. It is active in preparing youths for the Second Coming of Jesus Christ.

Strategies

The JSOS YUP! Movement ("yes" to Youth Level-UP) aims to upgrade the following aspects of the Ministry:

1. Organization
2. Intercession & Fasting
3. Discipleship
4. Evangelism
5. Camaraderie

The JSOS Christian Church had its obscure beginning way back in 1992.

That was after Pastor Jose C. Tacadena and his family (composed of wife Adelia, and children Jihrael and Jehannah ) left Manila where they had lived and ministered for six years. Having arrived in Angono, Rizal where his parents live, the couple was encouraged to hold regular Bible studies there.

The initial attendees were composed of that extended family ( parents Domingo and Maria, sisters Lydia, Perla, Rose and Tess, and older brother Romeo and his wife sis. Aida ), and a few faithful friends and co-workers in Christ from their previous Manila ministry. ( sisters Adah and Allaine Nicolas, Baby and Berna Aquino, and Jimmy Manarang ).

Later on, the turn of events confirmed God's leading to establish a local church right in Rainbow Village.  The house of Domingo Tacadena served as its house church then.

The name JESUS; SUPREME OVERRULING SHEPHERD CHRISTIAN church was chosen after much prayer and deliberation among the original incorporators primarily as a testimony of God's overruling supremacy in character and deeds, His overruling ability over all creations and principalities, and his unending personal love for every one, particularly for His sheep.

After five months of holding mere home Bible studies at the said house, the small group of believers finally had their first Sunday Morning Worship Service on June 28, 1992.  Since Tacadena's house was obviously not ideal for corporate worship, the JSOS initial members and leaders prayed for a larger area.

With God's mercy and provision, Delfin Tacadena, the pastor's eldest brother, bought a lot with unfinished house in front of the original sight. Brother Delfin developed it and lent it to the church to become it's official church worship center.

item.title: Truth Behind Its Name
item.dc:creator: jhesed
item.content:encoded:
[su_animate type="fadeInUp"]

The name JSOS was not decided upon by the small group of Christian incorporators through haphazard thinking and careless discussion. Instead, the name came about as a result of deep individual and group prayers and meditation not only on the Bible but also on certain events preceeding the establishment of the church that bears the said name.
After much prayerful discussion that lasted months, the incorporators of the said group were one in testifying that the name, " JESUS: Sovereign Overcoming Shepherd " is God-given for the specific purposes He has stored for this church.


[su_tabs vertical="yes" class="my-custom-tabs"]
[su_tab title="Sovereign"]

[one_fifth]

[/one_fifth]

[four_fifth_last]

That God is sovereign does not take away the fact that He still has many enemies. In fact, we, Christians have many enemies ourselves beginning with the chief opponent himself, Satan. In the Bible, Satan has mobilized his demonic forces to oppose God's people in every possible way. With God's loving and sovereign permission, the devil uses problems, sicknesses, failures, other people and even nature and circumstances to overcome us. But praise God because Jesus overrules all of them! In fact, Satan has thrown everything to Jesus in his attempt to defeat our Great Shepherd. But JESUS walloped him repeatedly from the temptation in the wilderness ( Matthew 4:1-11 ) to his resurrection from the dead. (John 10:17,18; 20:1-31; Colossians 2;9-15) Jesus overruled demons, sicknesses, nature, evil plots and people in the course of His earthly life. He will continue to do so until the total annihilation of all His enemies. 

[/four_fifth_last]

item.title: Doctrinal Statement
item.dc:creator: jhesed
item.content:encoded:
[su_animate type="fadeInUp"]

This is intended simply as a basis of fellowship among members of the JSOS Christian Church ( " . . . that we all speak the same things . . . " –1 Corinthians 1:10 ) . The wordings here are not inspired or contented for but the truth set forth is held to be essential to a full gospel Christian ministry.

No claim is made that it contains all biblical truths for the obvious reason that this is merely a partial list. Hence, the list may be added upon with supplementary and additional statements in the future.

However, we strongly believe that this list is Bible-based and is helpful for the identify and growth of the JSOS Christian Church.

 

[su_tabs vertical="yes" class="my-custom-tabs"]
[su_tab title="I.  The Bible"]

We believe in the scripture, both the Old and the New Testament comprising of books to be verbally inspired by God for men. These are inerrant ( faultless ) in writings and are thus the sole supreme authority in the rule of Christian faith and conduct ( 2 Timothy 3:16; 1 Thessalonians 2:13. 2 Peter 1:21 )

[/su_tab]


[su_tab title="II.  God"]

We believe in the one true God who has revealed Himself as the eternally Self- existent One, the Creator of heaven and earth, and the Redeemer of mankind. We further believe that this God reveals Himself to us in three distinctive existing persons: the Father, the Son and the Holy Spirit ( Matthew 28:19; 2 Corinthians 13:14; John 14:16,17 )

[/su_tab]


[su_tab title="III.  Jesus Christ"]

We believe in the Lord Jesus Christ as the eternal SON of GOD. As such, we believe in His:

A.      Virgin Birth and Humanity ( Matthew 1:23 ; Luke 1:31-35 )
B.     Deity (Hebrews 1:8 ; John 10:30 ; 20:28… )
C.     Sinless life ( Hebrews 7:26 ; 1 Peter 2:22 )
D.     Substitutionary and atoning death on the cross according to the Scripture ( 1 Corinthians 15:3 ; 2 Corinthians 5:21 )
E.      Bodily Resurrection from the dead ( Matthew 28:16 ; Luke 24:39 ; 1 Corinthians 15:4 )
F.     Ascension into heaven and exaltation to the right hand of God ( Acts 1:9 ;11 ; 22 Philippians 2:9-11 )

[/su_tab]

[su_tab title="IV.  Holy Spirit"]

We believe that the Holy Spirit is a divine person possessing all the attributes of deity. We further believe the following regarding Him:

A.      To the unbelievers

•      He convicts them of sin, righteousness and judgment ( John 16:5-11 )

B.      To the believers

1.     He baptizes them into the Body of Christ ( 1 Corinthians 12:13 )
2.     He causes their regeneration ( John 3:3-6 )
3.      He indwells them ( 1 Corinthians 6:14-16 )
4.      He fills them with Himself ( Ephesians 5:18 )
5.      He gives them spiritual gifts listed in the Bible for service in the church. ( 1 Corinthians 12:27-31 )

[/su_tab]

[su_tab title="V.  Man"]

We believe that man was created in the image of God. However, he sinned and thereby incurred not only physical death but also spiritual death which is separation to God. ( Genesis 1:26,27; 2:17; 3:6; Romans 5:12-19 )

We also believe that man is a tripartite being, body, soul and spirit ( 1 Thessalonians 5:23 )

[/su_tab]

[su_tab title="VI.  Salvation"]

We believe that salvation is only possible because of God’s grace and initiative, which is through the shed blood of Jesus Christ on the cross for us .

A.      Condition

Salvation is received through repentance and faith towards the Lord Jesus Christ ( Luke 24:47; Romans 10:13-15; Ephesians 2:8,9 )

B.     Evidence of Salvation

The inward witness of salvation is the direct witness of the Holy Spirit ( Romans 8:16 ) in the light and context of Biblical promises on it. ( 1 John 5 ) The outward evidence to all men is a life of righteousness and true holiness. ( Ephesians 4:24; Titus 2:12 )

[/su_tab]

[su_tab title="VII.  Sanctification"]

We believe that God desires sanctification for each of His child. Sanctification is an act of separation from that which is evil and of dedication unto God. ( Romans 12:1,2; 1 Thessalonians 5:3; Hebrews 13:13 ) This can be done by the power of the Lord Jesus Christ.

[/su_tab]

[su_tab title="VIII.  Justification"]

We believe that God’s children are justified. Justification is to acquit, declare righteous and pronounce sentence of acceptance into which one enters by faith. Justification is primarily a change of position on the part of the sinner. Once condemned, he is now acquitted; once under divine judgment, he is now the subject of divine commendation

The death and resurrection of Jesus Christ represent the outward provision for man’s salvation. The term justification has reference to the way in which the saying benefits of Christ’s death are made available for the individual. Faith is the means whereby the sinner lays hold of the benefit.

[/su_tab]

[su_tab title="IX.  Church"]

We believe that the church is the body of Christ, the habitation of God through the Holy Spirit with divine appointment for the fulfillment of her great commission. Every genuine Christian believer is an integral part of it. ( Ephesians 1L22,23; Hebrews 12;23 )

A.      ORDINANCES OF THE CHURCH

We believe that the Lord Jesus Christ has given the collective body of Christian believers two specific ordinances which we must do:

1.     BAPTISM IN WATER

This is to declare to the world that we have died with Christ and that we also have been raised with Him to walk in the newness of life. ( Matthew 28:19; Acts 10:47,48; Romans 6:4 )

2.     LORD'S SUPPER

This ordinance is to (1) symbolize our sharing the divine nature of our Lord Jesus Christ ( 2 Peter 1:4 ); (2) to commemorate His death ( 1 Corinthians 11:26 ); and (3) to anticipate His return ( 1 Corinthians 11:26 )

[/su_tab]

[su_tab title="X.  Second Coming of the Lord Jesus Christ"]

We believe in the literal, personal, glorious and pre-millennial return of the Lord Jesus Christ ( 1 Corinthians 15:51-57; Acts 1;11; 1 Thessalonians 4:13-18 ). We further believe of the following in relation to His return:

A.      TRANSLATION OR RAPTURE

We believe that in His coming, those who have died in Christ will be resurrected to be translated together with those who are still alive to meet JESUS in the air and to be with Him. ( 1 Thessalonians 4:16,17; Romans 8:23; Titus 2:13 )

The rapture will include all true Christians since the beginning of time, from all nations, cultures, denominations and sects.

B.      THE MILLENNEAL REIGN

We believe that after His return here, Jesus will reign with the saints on earth for one thousand years. ( Matthew 24:27-30; Revelations 1:7; 19:11-14 ). Jerusalem will be His capital of rule. At this time, the world’s population will continue to expand. Christians will be given specific positions and leadership tasks to fulfill.

C.      THE FINAL JUDGMENT

There will be a final judgment in which the wicked dead will be raised and judged according to their works. Whoever is not found written in the Book of Life will be consigned to everlasting punishment in the lake of fire. ( Matthew 25:46; Mark 9:43-49; Revelations 19:20; 20:11-15; 21:8 )

[/su_tab]

[su_tab title="XI.  Biblical and Comprehensive Worship"]

We believe that God desires to be praised and worshipped always specially by those who already know Him personally in the light of the Bible. ( John 4:20-24 ) In fact, we believe that worship is the main reason for man’s creation, existence and salvation . The main components of true worship is in truth and spirit.

A.      WORSHIP IN TRUTH

To worship God in truth is to worship Him in the light of His word, the Holy Bible.

1.      LIVING A RIGHTEOUS LIFE ( SANCTIFICATION )

By living in accordance to God’s commandments and directives, one is able to really worship and glorify God. This is the life that goes against the system of the world and is characterized by goodness, holiness and liveliness. ( Romans 12:1,2; Matthew 5:48 )

2.      SERVING GOD THROUGH ONE’S TALENTS AND SPIRITUAL GIFTS

We have been given various kinds of talents and skills. These are mainly meant to be used for glorifying God and edifying others. ( 1 Peter 4:9-10; 1 Corinthians 12 & 14 )

3.      ABOUNDING IN GOOD WORKS

Christians have been saved to abound in good works. They are in fact, Christ’s workmanship. ( Ephesians 2:6-9 ) We are commanded to abound in good works and are assured that our good works will never be in vain. ( 1 Corinthians 15:58; Galatians 6:9,10 )

4.      SUPPORTING THE WORKS OF GOD THROUGH FINANCIAL AND MATERIAL GIVING

Financial giving to support God’s works and workers, if done in an attitude of gratitude, love and cheerfulness, can be an effective way of worshipping God. This comes from a clear understanding that God’s works and workers here on earth need human participation to be fully accomplished and to be adequately supported, respectively. ( 2 Corinthians 8 & 9; Philippians 4:9, 19 )

5.      WINNING SOULS IN CHRIST

Leading other people to Christ in acts of repentance and acceptance of Him, is one of the best ways to worship and glorify God. It brings exultations in the heavens and high honors to the holiness, wisdom, power and love of God towards men. ( John 1:35-51; Luke 15:7; Acts 3:19; )

Soul-winning, therefore, is no just a Christian responsibility but a great Christian privilege as well. It’s indeed a privilege to let others come to God as repentant sinners and grateful worshipers. ( Acts 1:8; 2 Corinthians 5:10-21; Matthew 24:14; 28:18-20; Luke 24:47 )

B.     WORSHIP IN SPIRIT

To worship God in spirit is to worship Him from the depths of our inmost being: our hearts and mind. It is worship that is based on one’s devotion and love to God. ( Matthew 22:37 )

[/su_tab]

[su_tab title="XII.  Biblical Praise"]

We believe that praise, one of the more manifestative ways of honoring God, is so desired by Him from us that He has set forth ways how to do it. These include, among others, the following:

1.      verbal declarations of gratitude and adoration towards God ( Psalm 66:8,17; 98:4; Acts 6:4; Hebrews 13:15 )
2.      singing unto Him ( Psalm 47:6 )
3.      joyful noise for Him ( Psalm 66:1,2; 95:1 )
4.      musical instruments ( Psalms 33:2; 57:8; 150 )
5.      dancing before God ( Psalm 30:11; 149:3; 150:4 )
6.      lifting up hands towards Him ( Psalm 63:4; 134:2 )
7.      clapping of hands in honor of Him ( Psalm 47:1; 98:8 )

[/su_tab]

[su_tab title="XIII.  Divine Healing"]

We believe in divine healing as part of the gospel implications. Deliverance from sickness is provided for in the atonement and is a privilege of Christians. God’s healing manifestations include deliverance from direct demonic attacks like oppression, depression, obsession and even possession. ( Isaiah 53:4; Matthew 8:16,17; Psalm 103: 1-3 )

Divine healing may be directly given by God to its recipient in response to that person’s private prayer; or as an answer to the believing prayers of others, like the church elders, who have prayed for the sick and/or demonized. ( James 5:14-16; Matthew 8:1 – 9:8; Mark 16:17,18 )

[/su_tab]

[/su_tabs]

[/su_animate]

  1. History

    • First called as Music Ministry and first led by Bro. Rey Bonza.
    • Its name was changed to Praise Ministry through Bro. Christian Tacadena the director that time.
    • And was later on changed to Worship Ministry through Bro. Ronald Bolesa.
    • However, Worship is not limited to Music but should be integrated in our lifestyle.  Hence, Pastor Jose Tacadena renamed it to Praise and Music Ministry

  2. Name

    • MUSIC
      1. Music is just one of the many medium to worship God.
      2. There are three kinds of music - Christian music, secular music and worldly music.
    • PRAISE
      1. Praise is just one of the various forms of worshiping God.
      2. We can praise God through music or testifying God's goodness.
    • WORSHIP
      1. Worship is so much broader - it's not limited in music, praising and dancing.
      2. Worship is life - a Christian's lifestyle.

  3. Purpose Statement:

    • To lead the JSOS Church in corporate praise and worship of God: to inspire the congregation, through the Holy Spirit, to worship the Lord Jesus with all our heart, with all our soul, with all our mind and with all our strength

  4. Vision

    • The JSOS Church will become a God-worshiping and praising church - corporately and individually.
    • The JSOS Worship Ministry members will manifest the anointing as worship leaders, that through our ministry:
      1. People will be convicted by the Holy Spirit to come to Christ and make Him as their Lord and Savior;
      2. Sicknesses and diseases will be healed by God because of the overwhelming presence and power of the Holy Spirit;
      3. Spiritually weak and backsliding Christians will be revived and restored.
    • The JSOS Worship Team will be actively involved in supporting inter-church activities, such as concert, music fest, etc., that is glorifying to the name of our Lord Jesus Christ.

  5. Mission:

    • Spiritual revival in JSOS in worshipping the Lord Jesus Christ - congregationally and individually.
    • Every Worship Ministry member must manifest a worship life that is a level higher than those who are not.

item.title: Uncovering Myths About Love
item.dc:creator: jhesed
item.content:encoded:
Published in Mr & Ms Magazine
By Pastor Jose Tacadena

You’ve been feeling fine, but suddenly you’re hot, almost feverish. You can’t seem to get a hold to your breath. Your mouth feels it’s full of cotton. You try to speak but no sound comes out. You then try to move, but your limber muscles seem paralyzed.

Should someone call an ambulance? Are you about to have a heart attack at the peak of your youth?

No. It’s just that a special somebody you’ve hoping to get to know a lot better just walked into the room. You are in the initial stage of Localized Onset of Varied Emotions, more commonly known as LOVE.

There’s no need to see a doctor. He can’t help you. But it is time for intense scrutiny – some self-diagnosis. Although the symptoms of love are easy to identify, love itself is always misdefined. If that happens, you may fall for a fake—make—believe masquerading as the real thing.

How can you tell the difference? One important protection is to understand the myths that surround the true meaning of love.

Myth # 1: I know its love because of the way I feel

It is easy grow up believing love is just a feeling. After all, there are some very real feelings that accompany love – excitement, anticipation, surprise. However, if you measure love relationship by the feelings you experience, you’ve in for the biggest roller coaster ride of your life. Feelings are unpredictable. They give way quickly and can’t be a sure foundation, especially of a relationship.

Instead, it is important that your feelings be accompanied by actions of patience, kindness, courtesy, commitment, responsibility, honestly, integrity and purity. These are the foundation needed to build a relationship on.

Myth # 2: I know it’s love if it makes me happy

This is related to the first one because happiness is a feeling. Yet, there is more involved here than a feeling. Whose happiness are we talking about? Your happiness.

Describing love this way put you in the center and requires every activity, every emotion and every person add to your happiness. Although some people respect to find love with this formula, all that ever exist is self-centeredness. Self-centeredness eventually leads to isolation not love.

Myth # 3: I know its love because of physical attraction

Of course, there will be mysterious magnetic field pulling two people together when they are uncovering a love relationship. And there will be a chemistry that defies any formula. But there’s more to love than physics and chemistry.

The Bible tells us that our bodies are “fearfully and wonderfully made” (Psalms 139:14). This becomes unavoidably true in the area of physical reaction to the opposite sex.

When you are with that special someone, the brain begins sending chemically coded messages to other parts of the body. These signals result in physical reactions, fast heartbeat, sudden perspiration, even a feeling of euphoria. The only problem is that these signals only register physical attraction, not commitment and care for each other. While physical attraction is an essential ingrediaent in romantic love, it alone is not an indicator of true love.

MYTH # 4: I know it’s love when nothing else matters

Someone embracing this myth is saying, “As long as we’re in love we don’t have to worry about anything else.” When the intensity of physical attraction is the only way you identify real love, then, other important factors lurk in the shadows. The problem is that as you focus on intense feelings of attraction, differences such as age, maturity, spiritual commitment, and compatibility don’t seem to matter, After all, being analytical isn’t very romantic.

But real love looks at the difference. Real love does ask the tough questions. It listens to more than the answers of a heart in the middle of romantic feeling.

Another part of this myth surfaces in the area of neglected responsibilities. When two people in love focus on each other in a way that neglects everyone and everything else. What they call love is just a form of escapism. Real love, on the other hand, enjoys a relationship in the context of keeping commitments and respecting the rights of family and friends

MYTH # 5: I know its love when I don’t care what others think

Many accept this myth as truth. If a relationship goes against the good counsel of family and friends, the reaction is, “Who cares as long as we’ve got each other?”

On the surface, this may appear romantic and courageous; however, it is really another form of self-centeredness. Instead of announcing love’s inner stance in your life, you stubbornly proclaim that your perspective is the only one that counts.

Don’t be fooled by these myths. Unmask them by confronting the real definition of love that endures. St John the Apostle reminds us that God is love (I John 4:6)

Anything that lacks God’s honesty, integrity and purity is a counterfeit.

Why settle for anything less than real love at its best

item.title: Crying for "PAPA"
item.dc:creator: jhesed
item.content:encoded:
Published in Miscellanous Weekly Magazine

After two years, when the late night nursing were starting to exhaust my loving wife Del, I knew it was time for me to take over. At least, for the meantime.

Jhesed, our youngest kid, was then still accustomed to waking up five to six times from night to dawn. His craving for a newly prepared milk and the occasional call to pee were the culprits.

But I am a mega-sleeper, particularly after a hard day’s work. You guessed it. I did not look forward to being awakened randomly and many times during the wee hours of the day.

"I don’t know how you do it", I’d often said to Del. After all, she works harder than me and has more daily pressures but is more energetic to care for our kids.

I confess I balked at the unholy hours feeding party because Jhesed always awoke crying, "Mama, dede!" Of course, I’m not competing with my wife. But I admit I feel like a second fiddle mom, And not a very good one at that.

In fact, I even started out more as a hindrance than a help. Jhesed’s cries were not enough to wake em up although only my wife separates him from me on our family –sized bed.

I eventually decided to sleep just beside our child, and prayed that I become more sensitive to him. I also requested my wife to nudge me with here elbow whenever I failed to respond immediately our third child’s call.

The elbow and relentless cries for "mama" were not pleasant motivators, with the first whimper, I begun rationalizing, and then murmuring.

"Why does Jhesed have to continue sucking milk when he is already past two years old? Why do I have to volunteer doing this when Del could do it best?"

But still, the cry for "Mama" went on, Yawning, I sat up on bed and groped for the milk some two arms length away. I took a deep breath and announced hopefully, "papa is here, Just wait a minute."

To my pleasant surprise, Jhesed fell silent.

"Well, that wasn’t so hard," I thought and continued preparing his milk.

"Mamaaa!" the cry blasted forth with renewed vigor.

Startled, I stopped, then sighed. I tapped his shoulder with my left and whispered, "Jhesed, just wait."

Excitement pricked me, when as a response; my third child opened his eyes to look at me. Though the light was turned off, the full moon and the rays of the Meralco post lamp outside were clearly illuminating our second floor master’s bedroom. Our eyes met. Suspense grew inside me when Jhesed gave an impish smile.

But just as suddenly, he cried out again, Mammmmaaaaa! Dedee! shattering my eardrums as well as my ego. I gave him his milk and this quieted him.

Day after day, bottle after bottle, I pushed on through the cries for "Mama" – dutifully, if not lovingly, Soon however, I began to be sensitive to his cries.

I also begun to enjoy serving him, before long, I was even anticipating for that slight, uneasy move or simplest whimper to feed him early on, complete with a father’s touch.

On sentimental nights, I would embraced him and whisper to him some reassuring words, That his dad loves him-while he’s already contented with his milk, All these amidst the soft cries and pants for "Mama!".

And then late one night, it happened.

Lost in heavy sleep, I stirred as a strange sound tapped lightly on my ear. It wasn’t a cry, but more of a whisper.

"Pa-pa.."

My eyes flickered open, closed again. Shifting to my left, my head tilted back to get a good glimpse of my child.

"Pa-paaa! Pa-paaa!"

Bold and full throated, the small voice pier red the dark mornings like the horns of a triumphant politician.

My eyes exploded open. I was even more surprised to see my child gazing at me and smiling.

"Papa!" he whispered, "Papa, Dede"

Half lurching from bed , I scoped Jhesed in my arms. "That’s my son" I blurted out, "Yes that’s my son"

"What’s going on?" Del mumbled sleepishly. "What’s the noise all about?"

Sleepishly, I lowered Jhesed back on his place, My child appeared already awake at that time, but was not a bit uneasy. Concealing my excitement, I retorted to Del, "Nothing, I was just talking to Jhesed."

I begun to prepare his milk , I don’t know how many time I had been doing that, but this time, it was different,. Especially with Jhesed anticipating on his father’s service.

After receiving the bottle of milk, my child moved closer to me. He extended his left arm to my cheeks as if to appreciate what I’ve done. I tell you – it felt so good, real good.

Indeed, my should was impressed that night when I first heard my son call me "Papa"

Certainly, my joy came partly from waiting so long for him to acknowledge the bond between us, And yet when I had rejoiced fully and both he and Del were asleep again, I lay in bed staring at the stars visible from my views. I was gripped by something deeper.

I was identifying with the cry of my son, In his baby’s voice, I heard something I recognized in myself; I believe every man pants for that cry from the depths of his soul. It is the most basic cry for security, safety and love amidst a dark and lonely world, ‘Save me, Father God!’

I remember someone wrote, "Nothing will help you understand the love of God like having a child of your own". I think he was right.

May we fathers and mothers dare to listen to the cry for "Papa" in our own hearts so we can recognized it in our own kids and respond in love.

May everyone else hearten to his innate human cry for the Supreme Father in our lives, so that we can have greater peace, love and power that what we used to have as self-reliant. Self-made people

This is how we can fully understand God, who for His love for us has given us His every life, so that we will no longer be alienated to Him.

By believing in His Son Jesus, we can be empowered to be God’s children, whereby we cry to Him, "Abba (Daddy), Father!")

(I John 4:10, John 1:12, Romans 5:8)

item.title: Ang Patotoo ni Ronald Bolesa Jr.
item.dc:creator: jhesed
item.content:encoded:
Ang buhay ko ay maikukumpara ko sa isang paglalakbay, literal at simbolikal. Bata pa lang ako palipat-lipat na kami ng pamilya ko ng tirahan. Pinanganak ng Cebu City, nalipat ng Tondo, Apalit, Angono, Naga City, Legazpi City, Cardona at Taytay. Sadyang walang permanente sa mundo, lahat ay nagbabago.

Napakaraming mga masasama at masasakit na alaala mula pa lang pagkabata. Ilan sa mga ito ay di pa rin magawang malimutan dahil sa napakasalimuot na mga nasaksihan at naranasan.

Masasabi kong naging isang mabait na bata naman ako. Ngunit kung paanong nagbabago ang aking pisikal na kaanyuan,at ang mundo, gayon din naman ang pagbabago na nagaganap sa aking pagkatao. Pagtuntong ko ng high school ay nag-iba ang aking mga gawi at ugali. Naging palamura ako, at isang tila satanistang rakista (rock & roll), atbp.

Ibang-iba na nga ako. Di man kita ng iba, ayaw ko ng ganoong pagkatao. Noong bata pa ako lagi akong nagsa-sign of the cross. Sinisikap kong mahanap ang Diyos,gawin ang gusto Niya, maging mabait, baguhin ang sarili pero sadyang napakalakas ng hatak ng kamunduhan na tila wala ng puwang ang Krus sa puso ko. Paboritong linya ko ng rap ang “gusto kong bumait pero di ko magawa…nasa Diyos ang awa nasa tao ang gawa .“ Di ko pansin, isa na palang dasal ng puso kong gusto nang magbago ang awit na iyon.

Hindi ko alam na isang mas madilim na daan pa pala ang tatahakin ng aking paglalakbay. Kinse anyos ako ng isang pangyayari ang naganap: Agosto 22, 2000, Martes ng gabi, matutulog na sana kami, na-high blood ang papa ko. Na-comatose siya, at lumipas ang dalawang araw, tuluyan na siyang binawian ng buhay. Hinding-hindi ko malilimutan kung paano siya lumuha habang tinatakbo siya sa ospital: kung paano siya nag-aagaw-buhay sa I.C.U. Hinding-hindi ko siya malilimutan.

Lumipas ang mga araw, pagkatapos ng libing, sinikap naming maging normal ang buhay, pero napakahirap. Sa tuwing may dadaan na tricycle o titigil sa tapat ng bahay namin, tatayo kami at pupunta kami sa pintuan upang salubungin ang papa naming gaya ng nakasanayan namin, umaasa pa rin na sa pagbukas ng pinto ay si papa ang bubungad, pero ang katotohanan ay hanggang panaginip na lamang iyon. Dito na ako tuluyang naligaw. Sinubukan ang pag-inom ng alak, paninigarilyo, marijuana at maling relasyon. Napakahirap kumawala. Ayaw ko namang gawin ang mga iyon, pero ginagawa ko pa rin. Gusto ko nang magbago.

Kaya pinangarap kong magkaroon ng barkadang walang bisyo. Di naglaon ay nakilala ko sila Dagul, Ojen atbp. Naging solid ang tropa na iisa ang bisyo basketball. Sa tulong nila, nalayo ako sa masamang barkada. Minsan, kinausap kami ni Mark Go, sali raw kami sa paliga. Dahil libre, at adik nga kami dito, oo agad kami. Medyo pinalad kami, champion eh, iba talaga pag nagkakaamuyan na.

Pagkatapos ng liga, naging regular ang pagbisita ng team ni Ptr. Joe. Hinding-hindi ko malilimutan ang minsang naging deklarsyon ko pag-alis nila pastor (ang kukulit kasi eh): “hinding-hindi ako magiging born again.”

June 02, 2002, inimbitahan kami para sa awarding. Siyempre,kahit alam naming sa church ang lugar ng pagdadausan, pumunta kami, di kami pwede mawala doon. Lingid sa aming kaalaman, may plano pala ang Diyos sa amin ng araw na iyon. Nagbigay ng mensahe si Ptr. Joe at sa dulo nito, isang imbitasyon ng pagtanggap kay Jesus. Ayaw ko, kasi nakakahiya sa harap ng tropa, pero gusto ko rin, dahil matagal ko na Siyang hinahanap. Pero sa kadulo-duluhan, isa ako sa mga huling tumayo at lumapit sa altar upang tanggapin si Jesus bilang Panginoon ko at Tagapagligtas. Nanaig ang pagkauhaw ng aking kaluluwa. Bahala na kung ano ang iisipin ng mga barkada ko.

Naging regular na ang aking pag-atend ng J.S.O.S., pero dumating din ang punto na ako ay nanlamig at tuluyan na ngang nawala. Nagdesisyon na ako na wag nang magsimba. Maging sa mga outreach Bible studies ay di na rin ako sumasama.

Pero di nagsawa ang Diyos sa akin. Kinausap ako ni Dagul na bubuo ng basketball team ang JSOS, at ang makakasali lang sa line-up ay ang mga nagsisimba. Kaya sa motibasyon ng basketball, bumalik ako para makasali. Pero di ko inaasahan na yun na pala simula ng aking magiging lubusang pagsuko sa Diyos. Sa simbahan,habang nagbibigay ng mensahe ang pastor, isang pambihirang pagkilos ang ginawa ng Diyos. Sobrang nahaplos ang aking puso sa mensahe at unang beses kong naramdam ang Diyos. Umiiyak ako at sinabi ko sa Kanya, “di na ako magsisimba dahil sa basketball, kundi dahil sa Iyo.”

Napakarami pang nangyari sa buhay ko. Palipat-lipat ng lugar dahil sa sobrang kahirapan, at walang makain, grabe, gutom talaga. Minsan na akong namuhay ng mag-isa, salamat sa Bibliang (Bagong Tipan) bigay ni Kuya Chris, sa tulong nito natuto akong manalangin. Pagkalipas ng mahigit kumulang 3 buwan, napunta naman kami ng Cardona, kung saan pinakagrabe ang kahirapan, pero sa tulong ng Biblia (Lumang Tipan), naging matatag ako dahil sa inspirasyon ng mga kwento ng buhay ng tao sa Biblia.

Napakarami pang mga pagsubok ang aking hinarap, hinding-hindi ko malilimutan na minsang nasabi ko sa Kanya na “wala Kang kwentang Diyos”, dahil suko na ako. Pero di Siya nagbago, inibig Niya pa rin ako at inabot mula sa kadiliman.

Tunay na hindi maiiwasan ang mga pagsubok sa buhay, pero hindi na ako susukong muli dahil subok ko na ang pagmamahal ng Diyos sa akin na naging Ama ko sa aking pangungulila. Patuloy na magtitiwala at ipagkatitiwala ang aking buhay kay Jesus. Panghahawakan ko angKanyang pangakong magandang plano sa aking buhay, isang buhay na masagana at punong-puno ng pag-asa. Salamat Panginoon sa tiyak na kinabukasan (Jer. 29:11).Hindi man permanente at nagbabago ang mundo, iisa ang alam kong hinding-hindi magbabago, ang pag-ibig ng ating Diyos Ama sa atin.

item.title: Unti-unting Pagbabago
item.dc:creator: jhesed
item.content:encoded:
Bagamat namulat sa Children’s Sunday School, lumaki akong isang tambay -- naninigarilyo, umiinom ng alak kung minsan, at mahilig sa away. Sumasama rin ako sa fraternity at madalas makasaksi ng mga bugbugan. Hilig ko rin na mambato ng bubong ng ibang mga bahay. Kahit na hindi ako nakatikim, naranasan ko rin na makasilamuha sa mga humihithit ng marijuana.

Paano ko nakilala ang Panginoon

Ngunit dumating ang isang Linggo ng Sunday School na may pinaliwanag si tita Rose na nagpabago sa aking buhay. Gumamit siya ng isang maliit na booklet kung tawagin nila ay “Ang Sagot”. Doon ipinaliwanag ang kasalanan ng tao. At ayokong mapunta sa impyerno. Natakot ako. Kaya nagpasya akong tanggapin si Hesus sa puso ko.

Buhay ko ngayon

Kahit na hindi biglaan, mayroong pagbabago. Ngayong 16 years old na ako, natuto akong sumama sa mga Bible Study. Ang dating tinuturuan ay nagtuturo na rin sa mga follow-up sessions. Nagpapatanggap na sa Panginoon ang dating pinatanggap. At natututo na ring tumugtog ng drums para sa Panginoon.
